column168: While reloading the drums into another truck at the Veolia, Baytown, TX 10 day in-transit facility, small pins hole leaks were observed from 3 of the 4 drums.  Leaking did not occur until the drums were moved out of the truck and onto the dock area. The 3 leaking drums were immediately overpacked into 951H2 overpack drums.  At that time, the decision was made to also overpack the 4th non-leaking drum to prevent possible future issues while in transit.  While overpacking the drums, small pin hole leaks were observed from rust bubbles on the bottoms of the 3 drums. A total of 1/2 gallon spilled from the 3 drums and was cleaned up with absorbent pads and packed in the overpack drum.

DESIGNATED RESPONDER WAS CALLED FOR THE NOTICE OF A STRONG CHEMICAL SMELL. DR PUT ON BAGG PPE. IDENTIFIED LEAKING PACKAGE. FOLLOWED DT FOR A CLASS 3 HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PACKAGE. MOVED TO DMP FOR FURTHER PROCESSING

PACKAGE WAS ON HAZ-MAT PROCESSING TABLE. THERE WAS A SMALL AMOUNT OF GRAY POWDER LEAKING FROM THE BOX. THE BOX HAD DIAMOND LABEL UN0509 EXPLOSIVE 1.4C. THE CONTENTS WAS IN 2-1 GALLON CONTAINERS(OR 8 LBS CONTAINERS SINCE THE SUBSTANCE WAS A POWDER). THE CAPS POPPED OFF BOTH CONTAINERS. SMALL AMOUNT OF POWDER LEAKED OUT. TOOK ALL THE POWDER IN THE SPILL TUB, USED A PAPER FUNNEL PLACED THE LEAKING POWDER IN THE CONTAINERS FOR PROCESSING. BOTH CONTAINERS PLACED BACK IN THE BOX. AND THE BOX WAS PLACED IN A GREEN DMP BAG FOR PROCESSING. AWAITING FURTHER INSTRUCTIONS FROM VEOLIA FOR DISPOSAL.
UNLOADER NOTICED PACKAGE WAS WET AND LEFT AREA TO NOTIFY SUPERVISOR WHO THEN NOTIFIED HAZMAT RESPONDER

WE RECEIVED A CALL INDICATING THERE WAS A SPILL OF A DECLARED HAZMAT AT DOOR 12 IN THE WEST UNLOAD. WENT TO INVESTIGATE THE SPILL WHILE I PUT ON MY PROPER PPE (BOOTS, APRON, GOGGLES AND GLOVES). I WAS INFORMED THAT THE SPILL WAS IN FACT A DECLARED HAZMAT AND THAT IT WAS CORROSIVE AND LAYING ON IT'S SIDE IN THE TRAILER. WHEN I ARRIVED AT THE SPILL I PROCEDED TO FOLLOW THE PROPER PROCEDURES AS INDICATED IN THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET FOR A CORROSIVE SPILL. NO LIQUID WAS SPILLED OUTSIDE OF THE PACKAGE BUT THE PACKAGE WAS WET FROM THE INSIDE SO I RETRIEVED THE PACKAGE AND TRANSPORTED IT BACK TO DMP FOR PROCESSING.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On 2/2/21, FRA Hazmat Inspector R. Boyington identified the UTLX 300055 as having residue near the pressure relief device.  Mr. Boyington notified BNSF which then isolated the car and notified hazmat responders to inspect and clean the car.  Upon inspection, the valve appeared to be in good condition and closed.  Acid was found on the valve and the stain on both sides of the car body.  The acid was neutalized and cleaned from the tank car.  A pressure test was conducted to determine whether the car could move safely to destination.  The pressure test confirmed that the valve was closed and containing the product to 30 psi.  It has not been determined when, where or why the valve leaked acid.  The dates, times and findings are represented as BNSF observed them.
column169: Recommend that the shipper/car owner perform a bench test of the valve to ensure that the set pressure for valve activation is within range.

column168: On 02/04/2021, at 0312 hours, personnel in the CSXT Parkersburg Yard discovered CTCX 780290, a residue tank car of Butadienes, leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and Kraton Polymers, National Response Center, West Virginia DEP, and the Federal Railroad Administration were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2021-0204-00018). Specialized Professional Services, Inc, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the A-end Liquid Valve a quarter turn open and the secondary closure plug less than tool tight. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Aimee Dose, phone 904-349-9028. Contractor personnel closed the valve and installed the secondary closure tool tight thus securing the release. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move.   Cause Code: 117 NARRI: 36

column168: At 1115 Hours on 1/30/2021, the Wheeling and Lake Erie Switch Crew in Brewster Yard noticed an odor coming from tank car TILX 302628 and then contacted the Brewster Yardmaster who then called myself, John Vergis Hazardous Materials/Environmental Officer for the WLE.  I came out to look at the car that was in 15 track and when I investigated, I found that the liquid valve on the B end on the car was frosted and leaking through the valve plug.  I tried to tighten the valve handle to see if the leak would stop and it did once tightened.  I only got a very slight turn turn on the valve.  I then tried to tighten the valve plug to see if it was loose.  It was slightly loose but not enough to cause a leak.  I took the plug out and installed some more Teflon tape on the threads and then reinstalled the plug.  I then released the car for service at 1145 hrs.  NARRI: 2(4+5+0)x(2+0)=36                              Cause Codes:115-117
column169: Other than not putting enough sealant on the threads of the plug, I do not think it was prepared improperly.  I believe this style of valve is defective.  I see this a lot.

column168: A warehouse employee was loading pallets of drums on to a van trailer with a fork lift. Two drums had to be loaded with a dolly and were positioned on the trailer without being on a pallet. When the fork lift operator loaded the next pallet of drums, one of the forks protruding from the front of the pallet being loaded punctured one of the 30 gal. steel drums that was not on a pallet causing a large hole near the bottom of the drum and allowing nearly all of the contents to be released, approx. 25 gal.
column169: The fork lift operator underwent remedial training in the use and operation of the fork lift for loading / unloading. The operator also underwent remedial training in the use of other equipment that would have negated the two drums being dollied on the trailer without being placed on a pallet. The operator was placed under a senior employee to receive additional training and coaching.

column168: THE PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED, PALED AND SORTED TO THE SOUTH SORT AISLE. THERE THE PACKAGE WAS SORTED INTO THE APPROPRIATE CAGE IN THE BOX LINE. THE PRE-LOADER NOTICE AN ODOR AND A LIQUID SUBSTANCE IN HIS CAGE. HE LEFT THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR. THE SUPERVISOR CALLED FOR A DESIGNATED RESPONDER. THE RESPONDER, FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE AND A THE APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET, PLACED THE PACKAGE INTO A LINED SPILL TUB. THE EQUIPMENT WAS CLEANED FOLLOWING THE DECONTAMINATION CHECKLIST. THE PACKAGE WAS THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. IT WAS THERE THE PACKAGE WAS DETERMINED TO BE UNDECLARED.
THE PACKAGE LOOKED LIKE IT HAD BEEN WET AT ONE TIME. I RESPONDED AND INVESTIGATED THE PACKAGE.

BACK UP RESPONDER WAS CALLED TO UNLOAD DOOR 11 AT 4:15. RETRIEVE DAMAGED PACKAGE. TOOK TO PSC FOR INSPECTION. UPON INSPECTION PRIMARY RESPONDER DISCOVERED CONTENTS WERE NOT ON THE NON-REGULATED LIST. SDS WAS OBTAINED WHERE SECTION 14 SHOWED PROPER SHIPPING NAME, HAZARD CLASS, UN NUMBER AND PACKING GROUP. RMP WAS NOTIFIED. HMSC WAS CALLED.

DRIVER COULDN'T LOCATE PACKAGE WHEN INITIALLY AT THE DELIVERY STOP. WHEN THE DRIVER DID LOCATE THE PACKAGE, IT HAD A VISIBLE HOLE IN THE PACKAGE AND APPEARED WET. DRIVER NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR AND RMP WENT OUT TO ASSESS THE SPILL AND RECOVER THE PACKAGE. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT NO SPILLAGE HAD OCCURRED ONTO OTHER PACKAGES OR IN THE VEHICLE, AND THAT THE DAMAGE TO THE PACKAGE WAS CAUSED INSIDE THE PACKAGE ITSELF. RMP BROUGHT PACKAGE BACK TO THE FACILITY TO PROPERLY PROCESS.

RESPONDED TO LEAKING PACKAGE USING PROPER RESPONSE PROCEDURES. WHILE INSPECTING, DISCOVERED UNDECLARED HAZMAT CONTENTS INSIDE. CONTACTED HMSC INSTRUCTED TO HOLD FOR INSTRUCTION UNTIL RELEASED BY UPS ADG AGENT.
PACKAGE TORN / INSIDE CONTAINER BENT
IRREG PERSONNEL IMPROPERLY HANDLED PACKAGE. PACKAGE DELIBERATELY ABRADED AGAINST ROUGH EDGE OF METAL IRREG CART, CAUSING A PUNCTURE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM

column168: On 2/23/2021 at 2026 personnel in the CSXT Doyle Yard discovered PROX23012, a loaded tank car of  styrene leaking from electronic gauging device. The car was isolated and Shell Chemical Canada,  Kentucky Division of Emergency Management and the National Response Center were notified  CHEMTREC Report #2021022300320. Marion Environmental Inc., a CSXT response contractor, was  dispatched to the scene and found a liquid leak in the protective housing. The issue identified and  corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Rick Ferguson 832-712-9770. Contractor  personnel were able to remove the electronic gauging device and plug the port on the pressure  plate stopping the leak. The 1-cup of material in the protective housing and sides of the car  evaporated and did not require cleanup. There was not any impaction to the ground. The leak was  secured and the car released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move.  NAR Cause Code: 662 – Electronic Gauging Device / Housing cracked.  2(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 24 NARRI

column168: During a switch move, product was noted to be leaking down the sides of the car.  Car was isolated and environmental contractor called to respond.  Investigation revealed liquid around the threads of the plug in the liquid line and vapors (600+ VOC) coming from the hinge area of the manway cover plate.  All manway bolts were tight and further tightening them did not stop the leak.  Bolts were loosened, gasket removed and replaced.  Bolts were retightened in star pattern and seal checked for leaks.  none found.  Liquid line plug was removed, large amount of Teflon tape was brushed off, Teflon tape reapplied and plug was tightened wrench tight and checked for leaks.  Car was sealed and released back in to transportation.

Employee was removing drum from the waste storage area. There is a curb surrounding the waste storage area. This curb causes a slight, but sharp drop down as you are moving the drum, The employee navigated that drop, and felt the drum "bounce". As he was placing the drum behind the truck, he heard liquid running, and noticed liquid being released from the bottom of the drum. When the drum was jarred, it appears that the foot of the drum dolly had punctured the bottom of the drum.  The employee laid the drum on it's side, and positioned the hole so no more liquid would run out. The employee used absorbent pads to stop the liquid, however some if the liquid got into a trench and catch basin.  A Clean Harbors field service crew was called in to complete the clean up. The flied service crew. blocked off the drains from the catch basin, and used the appropriate intrinsically safe pump to remove the liquid and placed that liquid into a new drum. The area was rinsed off, and the rinsate was also placed into that drum. The sludge in the bottom of the catch basin was removed, and placed into a drum along with the absorbent material and used PPE. All of the drums were then shipped off to their final destination
column169: Employee retrained on equipment inspection. The drum dolly in question was taken out of service and replaced.

column162: DIRECTOR OF TRADE COMPLIANCE - THE AMERICAS
column168: The shipper, Quadion, LLC advised that prior to this shipment, the item was mistakenly flagged as non-hazardous in their ERP system.  Because of this, when the pick slip was printed to fill the order no indication was visible on the document that this was a hazardous item and that it required classification, declaration, marking and labeling.  The shipper realized the issue when the container was intransit to the port of export.  The shipper advised the forwarder (Expeditors) of the issue.  Expeditors worked with the shipper to help find a solution.  The shipper worked with a DG packer (Hazmat Express LLC) to remove the DG goods from the container, so they can be properly marked & labeled and a DG declaration can be prepared.  The DG goods are being held at the DG packer awaiting instructions for shipping.
column169: The shipper, Quadion, LLC has advised that they have now flagged this item in their ERP system as being hazardous.  They have also populated the DG classification information in the notes within their ERP system.  Going forward, every time a pick slip prints with this item included, the following verbiage will be printed on the form and the person filling the order will see:  "Hazardous Item.  Export shipment of this item must move as an individual shipment via Expeditors.  Item must first be professionally hazmat export packaged.  Contact Corporate Logistics to arrange."

column168: On 02/24/2021, at 0811 hours, A Carman in discovered the GATX81826, a Residue UN 1193 ETHYL METHYL KETONE ,having a Vapor  release from the vacuum relief devices. The railcars were isolated and National Response Center and the NY Department of environmental Conservation were notified. The emergency response telephone number on the waybill was contacted, (CHEMTREC Report #20210224-00080), and Shell Chemical LP the shipper of record was notified. Marion Environmental a CSX response contractor was dispatched to the scene and found the vacuum relief device on both railcars having a vapor release. The Vacuum relief device was removed and replaced with a plug securing the release. The release was secured and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. The railcar was placed on Hazmat hold and will require Shippers MRU to correct the defects. This incident did not require a special switching move.

column168: On 2/16/2021 a small leak from a 3 gallon plastic drum (31H1) was discovered upon arrival at the Veolia, Marlborough, MA office. Employees offloading supplies from the truck noticed a solvent small. They inspected the truck and found a 3 gallon plastic carboy (31H1) with a small leak. Upon further investigation it was determined that there was a small crack in the drum on the bottom of the container. The leaking drum was overpacked into a 30 1H2 drum to continue transportation to the treatment storage and disposal facility.     The drum leaked less than 1 pint of mixed solvents while in transit due to the crack. The liquid was cleaned up with spill pads and absorbent and the drum was overpacked into an appropriate 30 gallon drum along with the other container of the same material that had not leaked. The duration of release is anticipated to be a small drip from the drum for about 2 hours with no more than a quart leaking.   The Veolia safety manager was immediately notified upon discovery of the spill. The final root cause of the incident was determined to be that a drum had a small  crack in it due to the age of the container. The container had been at the shipper location for quite a while as they had issues with their previous vendor and then switched over to Veolia as a new vendor. The container was inspected prior to shipping and did not have any issues. It appears that the leak was caused when the container was in transit as a very small crack seemed to occur during normal transportation when discovered at end of the trip.
column169: The cause of a spill was that a crack developed in a 3 gallon drum during normal transportation. Veolia employees must continue to inspect drums when handling prior to and during transportation and notify management upon discovery of a leaking container. Veolia will continue to review the causes of spills with employees the best method to overpack a leaking container or to prevent any further leaking of containers. In this particular case, the container was inspected and appeared to be in safe condition to transport as offered. During the investigation, it was discovered that the container was old as the shipper had issues with their previous waste vendor. Due to those issues, the shipper started using the services of Veolia. Veolia intends to pick up their clients waste on a more regular basis to avoid this issue from reoccurring.

The impact of the release was to the trailer, dock and warehouse floor, with no threat to life, water, storm drains or land. In appropriate personnel protective equipment, trained facility personnel were successful in overpacking the compromised container into an authorized package. All impacted areas were remediated and the container was sent to its final destination without further incident.

column168: At approximately 0200 2/18/2021 an employee reported for work and discovered a hazardous waste trailer had caught fire. The employee called 911, and police an fire responded. AT approximately 0600 all flames and hot spots had been extinguished, and the fire department left by 0630. All the contaminated fire fighting water was contained with in the secondary containment area, and the underground storm water drain trench. The valve to the storm water pond was closed, so no contaminated water reached the pond. Containment area, and underground trench were drained, and the water was shipped off for disposal. All of the debris from the fire, including the wood floor was collected, placed into containers, and shipped for disposal. The frame, and sides of the trailer were also cut up, and shipped off for disposal. The area of the fire was cleaned of all soot, and fire debris. All rinsate was collected and shipped for disposal. Included in the attachments is a list of all the materials that were destroyed in the fire. The list includes manifest numbers, and waste descriptions.
column169: The facility will eliminated the use of "storage trailers", and will only use road worthy trailers and build specific outbound loads. All facility personnel will receive re-training on load segregation. column168: Employee was taking container from the customer drum storage area to the truck. The only way to the truck was down 6 stairs. Instead of leaving the container, or waiting for a forklift, the employee attempted to use the drum dolly, and take the drum down the stairs. After the first stair, the employee found the container to be to heavy to control, and the drum fell down the stairs. The top chime and lid of the drum were crushed during the fall, causing the paint to release on the concrete parking lot.  Absorbent material was used to stop the spread of the paint waste, and to absorb the material. The clean up material was placed into a new drum. A crew was dispatched to clean up the site.
column169: The employee was retrained. Emphasis was placed on the safety aspect of moving a drum, and how is never acceptable to take a full drum up or down a flight of stairs.

column168: We received a shipment from LHR via ATL of 7 skids. While offloading the shipment from the truck I noticed that one of the skids contained multiple boxes with the Limited Quantities label. There is nothing on the AWB indicating that the shipment is DG in limited quantities. There is no shipper's Dec either and none of the boxes have a UN number. The AWB states in the nature and quantity of goods box that this is a shipment of beauty products. This may be a potential undeclared dangerous goods incident. I have taken photos of both the AWB and the boxes labeled with the limited quantity marks.
column169: It is difficult to pinpoint one singular issue as to the root cause, there were numerous errors here. The Agent did not declare as dangerous goods, the labels were not noticed on the door by the warehouseman or by the builder who built the flight. It also appears the shrink wrap was very cloudy which could have made it difficult for anyone to spot any HAZ labels. The Agent has not tendered the freight correctly, there are also no hazardous class labels which may have been more obvious to spot.  To conclude this incident, I would suggest the Agent is responsible for presenting the incorrect paperwork and incorrectly labelled cargo. For our part if anything, we could have checked over the cargo with more attention, but I would not say the warehouseman did his role to the best of his ability. As can be seen in the photograph, it would not have been easy to see through the cloudy shrink wrap, there were no DG classification labels and nothing flagged up on the HHT device. The builder would have also had no triggers to alert him the consignment was hazardous, because of this his eye would not necessarily have notice the limited quantity labels either.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s  location to the intended waste management facility. During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the  purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued  transportation. During the transfer operation, it was discovered that approximately 1 gallon of  material had escaped from a pinhole leak that had developed in the container.  Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised container  into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris and materials used to decontaminate  the floor of the trailer were collected and placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the  container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was  observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during staging period as well as before it is loaded and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced  structural integrity.  IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and have been asked to inspect all  containers used for the transport of waste materials to insure they meet all required specifications.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: On February 23, 2021 at 1723 ET, two (2) 275 - gallon poly totes containing UN1840, Zinc Chloride Solution, 8, PGIII (Marine Pollutant) were discovered to be leaking due to a pinhole puncture resulting in approximately 50 gallons of product to release impacting the asphalt roadway and trailer floor. Haz Mat Special Services LLC was dispatched out of Beaumont, TX to perform emergency response and cleanup activities. The contractor neutralized the impacted surfaces and also utilized granular absorbents to recover the free product. The impacted absorbents and spent neutralizer were collected and containerized into two (2) 55 - gallon poly drums. The product remaining in the two totes were transferred into two (2) new totes. Haz Mat Special Services LLC personnel then departed the site with the waste generated.

On February 25, 2021, TCIX 210120 was discovered leaking Sodium Hydrosulfide (UN2922) from the B-end near the stub sill. A Hazmat contractor was called out and spill containment was placed under the leak and remained there until the contents of the car could be transferred.  Interior inspection revealed a 10-inch horizontal crack in the B-head end of the tank. The crack was not visible from the outside and no visible damage to the jacket or brake handle assembly.
column169: During the pre-loading process of older jacketed cars like this, particular attention should be paid to the undercarriage/stub sill area to be sure there is no evidence of leaks that have occurred. Use this as a case study for the loading/inspection staff.(NAR:658)

column25: Schneider National Inc. for Assoc. Logi
column168: ODOT Hazmat Inspector Ray Hubbell notified Portland IMF personnel of a hazardous leak discovered during his destination audit of unit  SNLU 206979. BNSF LARS received notification and dispatched US Ecology for remediation. Inspection revealed hazardous palletized bagged fertilizer  (calcium nitrate     UN 1454), loaded in what appeared to be 1X2X2X2X2X2 pattern from nose to rear. Securement was deficient without any lateral  securement observed (zero centerline void filler), and one insufficient 2X4 across the rear appearing to be laminated floor blocking. The lack of  securement allowed the cargo to migrate, one bag from the second row of pallets fell to the floor puncturing it which caused the leakage of hazardous  product. US Ecology remediated the excess and sealed the bag.
column169: Ensure that the beneficial shipper is aware of this and securement requirements to ship on rail and in accordance with BNSF   s Intermodal Rules and Policies Guide.

column25: Fedex Freight Inc (s/b Earth Science Lab
column168: Shipment arrived at Destination in Stockton, CA and was reported as a possible leaking load upon deramp. Personnel reported a dry blue powder on the underside of the container and railcar. This shipment was listed as containing hazmat. Patriot Environmental was dispatched to inspect and remediate. Upon arrival, contractor performed an exterior inspection which revealed dried blue residue on the under side of the container. An interior inspection was also performed and that resulted in finding several 55 gallon drums of "Agritec Algaecide", a corrrosive pesticide that had leaked from caps that were loose. Contractor estimated that a total of 1/2 gallon of product leaked over several drums. Contractor cleaned affected exterior and interior areas of the trailer, cleaned and tightened drum caps, and sealed caps with duct tape to prevent them from loosening during further transit. Contractor completed remediation and departed facility at approximately 13:30.

• The driver confirmed it was the correct product going to correct customer tank and hooked up for unload.   • He was using 80 feet of delivery hose connected to our trailer by way of a 3” double female fitting. The  other end (2”) was connected directly to the customer tank.   • The driver opened the internal valve (and cracked open the external) to begin the unload. o The Schneider trailer has two valves that must be opened to allow for product flow (an internal and external valve).  The internal valve works on hydraulics and is either all the way open or all the way closed.   o The external valve is a hand turn wheel that can be partially opened to get the desired flow rate.  Consistent with our training he ‘cracked open’ the external hand wheel to allow product to slowly fill the hoses and check for product leaks.   o Air pressure was at 15psi (standard air pressure tolerance) • He walked the hose line to the customer tank and didn’t observe any leaks and validated that the customer tank meter was showing that it was receiving product (trickling).   • Robert walked back to the trailer and proceeded to open the external valve the rest of the way. • As soon as the valve was fully open the fitting (one of the camlock arms) connected to our hose broke allowing the hose to release which spilled 20-25 gallons of product before driver was able to shut it down.   •  (Refer to illustrations below) • The camlock arm snapped off at the base where it pivots allowing the hose to become disconnected.    • The driver was startled when the release occurred, and instinctively lunged backwards out of the way, allowing for some product to get under the face shield.   • He quickly shut the internal valve on the trailer to stop product flow and ran to the safety shower.   • The safety shower was ice cold, and the driver stood in for as long as he could tolerate, got out to warm up, called Schneider, and stated he had asked for an ambulance. He got back in the shower one more time and waited for ambulance. o Driver was treated and released the same day without restrictions   Root Cause • The camclock ear failed o There was not a cause visible to the human eye - assume it is metal fatigue. ¿ We learned that driver leaves this fitting attached to the hose for a duration of one month intervals, of which he replaces the gaskets inside the fitting.  In between deliveries the hose and the attached fitting are hanging from the hose rack allowing it opportunity to come in to contact with other parts of the vehicle. Standard practice would be to put into a fitting box.   o There is no trend to this type of failure- first incident   Contributing Factors • Driver was storing his fittings improperly • Driver had difficulty tolerating the temperature of the safety shower
column169: Corrective Actions: • Driver has been coached on properly storing fittings  • We are reviewing this specific fitting at a company shop to ensure there are no missed contributing factors or root cause cause  o Update: Per our shop technician no visible damage could have been seen as part of a visual inspection. Camlock arm failed- no specific root cause/many causal factors- potentially age of the camlock, general use and storage, general wear and tear.  • A fleet macro will be sent reminding drivers not to transport their hoses with fittings attached and to carefully visually inspect camlocks for any signs of damage Submit DAR to Ecolab to request their customer review the water temperature for their emergency shower

column168: The accident occurred on Route US-220 (single lane in each direction) approximately 0.2 miles north of its intersection with Route 605 near Mustoe in Highland County, Virginia. The weather at the time of the accident was clear, although it apparently rained the day or night before. The accident occurred at 7:07 a.m. Reliable knows this because the truck is equipped with GPS. Between 7:07 and 7:08 a.m., the GPS shows the truck went from 42 mph to 4 mph. At 7:08 a.m., the ignition on the truck turned off. It appears the driver was driving within the speed limit.  The accident occurred when the front wheel of the transport tanker went onto a soft roadside shoulder. The shoulder gave way and allowed the truck to roll down an embankment. Gasoline from the truck began leaking almost immediately and went directly into the Jackson River. The puncture was 1-1/2" +/- in diameter along the top center of the tanker shell about 2' behind the manhole lid for compartment #1. The driver immediately applied spill pads to capture product leaking from the tanker into the river. There was damage to the front/right corner of the tanker, but no puncture or tear (see attached photo). First responders deployed sorbent booms in the river. DEQ called in W.E.L., Inc., an environmental response contractor. WEL deployed additional booms, and then maintained the booms until cleared for removal by DEQ days later. DEQ determined no soil or other remediation was required. Reliable has calculated that 1,470 gallons were released into the river.
column169: Speed was not a factor. Lane departure onto a soft shoulder caused the loss of control. This presents an opportunity to address the extra importance of anticipating route conditions and staying mentally alert during all parts of every trip, familiar and unfamiliar.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column25: Schneider National Inc. for Assoc. Logi
column168: ODOT Hazmat Inspector Ray Hubbell notified Portland IMF personnel of a hazardous leak discovered during his destination audit of unit  SNLU 206979. BNSF LARS received notification and dispatched US Ecology for remediation. Inspection revealed hazardous palletized bagged fertilizer  (calcium nitrate     UN 1454), loaded in what appeared to be 1X2X2X2X2X2 pattern from nose to rear. Securement was deficient without any lateral  securement observed (zero centerline void filler), and one insufficient 2X4 across the rear appearing to be laminated floor blocking. The lack of  securement allowed the cargo to migrate, one bag from the second row of pallets fell to the floor puncturing it which caused the leakage of hazardous  product. US Ecology remediated the excess and sealed the bag.
column169: Ensure that the beneficial shipper is aware of this and securement requirements to ship on rail and in accordance with BNSF   s Intermodal Rules and Policies Guide.

column25: Fedex Freight Inc (s/b Earth Science Lab
column168: Shipment arrived at Destination in Stockton, CA and was reported as a possible leaking load upon deramp. Personnel reported a dry blue powder on the underside of the container and railcar. This shipment was listed as containing hazmat. Patriot Environmental was dispatched to inspect and remediate. Upon arrival, contractor performed an exterior inspection which revealed dried blue residue on the under side of the container. An interior inspection was also performed and that resulted in finding several 55 gallon drums of "Agritec Algaecide", a corrrosive pesticide that had leaked from caps that were loose. Contractor estimated that a total of 1/2 gallon of product leaked over several drums. Contractor cleaned affected exterior and interior areas of the trailer, cleaned and tightened drum caps, and sealed caps with duct tape to prevent them from loosening during further transit. Contractor completed remediation and departed facility at approximately 13:30.

During inspection at the Tokyo gateway a package was discovered with the wording Dangerous Goods in Excepted Quantiles UN1995. The package contained a EQ mark with a "3." However, on the MAWB the wording Dangerous Excepted Quantities was not included.

column168: Due to circumstances not yet determined , our tractor and tank trailer ended up jack-knifed on Hwy. 20 in Iowa While jack knifed another Class A vehicle ran under our trailer causing the trailer to start leaking from an unknown location.  The Iowa State Patrol, Waterloo Fire & Rescue and Hazmat one were called to the scene.  The sulfuric acid release was dammed up and covered with soda ash. The remaining product was off loaded from the trailer and pumped into another Barto Trucking trailer and hauled back to Barto trucking. The spilled product and contaminated soil were disposed of by Waste Mangement Co. We do not yet have possession of our tractor and trailer to complete our investigation.

column168: DRIVER WAS DRIVING DOWN HIGHWAY 96 HEADED NORTHBOUND WHEN COMING OVER A BLIND OVERPASS CONSTRUCTIONS CREWS HAD THE HIGHWAY MERGING INTO ONE LANE. DRIVER HAD TO BRAKE HARD IN ORDER NOT TO CAUSE AN ACCIDENT AND REAR END THE CARS IN FRONT OF HIM. THIS CAUSED THE LOAD TO SHIFT IN THE ROLL- OFF BOX (NON SPECIFICATION SIFT PROOF BULK BIN AND CAUSED THE INNER LINER TO BE BREACHED CAUSING THE FREE LIQUIDS INSIDE THE INNER CONTAINER TO BE RELEASED OVER THE RAIL OF THE ROLL OFF CONTAINER.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED OFF THE FREEWAY AND NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISION.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW WERE DEPLOYED AND FIRE DEPARTMENT, TX DOT, AND THE GENERATOR OF THE WASTE ( LUCITE) WERE NOTIFIED .  AMOUNT OF RELEASE IS ESTIMATED AT 25 GALLONS. OIL DRY WAS USED TO SOLIDIFY THE WASTE AND DECONTAMINATION FACILITY PHOENIX INDUSTRIAL WATER WORKS AND PROPERLY DECONTAMINATED. ALL WASTE GENERATED FROM THE CLEAN UP PROCESS WAS COLLECTED INTO ANOTHER ROLL OFF BOX AND WILL BE TAKEN FOR DISPOSAL AT THE PROPER DISPOSAL FACILITY.
column169: POST INCIDENT. IT WAS DISCOVERED THE ORIGINAL SAMPLE PROVIDED BY THE GENERATOR FOR PROFILING PURPOSES WAS NOT FROM THE SAME TANK OF THE LOADED PRODUCT INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT. MULTIPLE TANKS CONTAINING THIS PRODUCT WERE BEING CLEANED AT THE GENERATORS FCILITY.  THE SOLIDIFIED SAMPLE PROVIDED WAS PLACED PN A DESK AT THE FACILITY FOR OVER A YEAR PRIOR TO BEING PROVIDED FOR SAMPLING. THIS LED TO AN INADEQUATE PREPARATION  FOR TRANSPORTATION.  FURTHERMORE , AN INVESTIGATION INTO US ECOLOGY / NRC GULF ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES INVOLVEMENT, IT WAS  DISCOVERED THE DRIVER CONDUCTED AN EXTERIOR INSPECTION OF THE LOAD , BUT DID NOT OPEN THE TOP COVER OF THE NON- SPECIFICATION SIFT -PROOF BULK BIN TO INSPECT THE INTERIOR FOR PACKAGING OE SECUREMENT.

column42: HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 5 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 16 PERCENT AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: On February 09,2021, at approximately 14:42, Welsh Power Plant received a delivery of 4,895.62 gallons of sodium hypochlorite. The shipment originated at Brenntag Southwest in Houston, TX and was transported to Pittsburg, TX in a cargo tank vehicle by Unden Bulk Transportation. The bill of lading number was 129176. Two equipment operators(EO) were coordinating the:unloading of the truck. One EO was stationed with the truck at the remote unloading connection located West of the Administration building. The other EO was stationed at the tank itself, located at the lake. The remote unloading point is connected to the product storage tank by approximately 800 feet of 4-inch diameter CPVC product transfer piping located underground. Both the product storage tank and piping are consignee-owned. The EO atttie truck was responsible for making sure the truck loaded with what we were expecting(sodium hypochlorite 10%, or bleach, seeing that the truck was safely and correciiy hooked up to the connection point The EO at tank was responsible for making sure the valves at the tank it self were lined up correctly. Once the bleach was being moved to the tank, EO at truck contacted EO at tank on the radio to confi,rn that we did have flow to the tank. EO at tank confirmed that indeed, there was bleach flow to the tank. EO at truck and shift supefvisor saw the local level Indicator increase in value. Shift supervisor returned to the EPS office and received a call from maintenance supervisor that a mechanic had noticed what appeared to be a water leak on the Ash Pond side of the road directly West of the Bleach tank. EO at the tank would not have been able to see this from his vantage point at the tank. Shift supervisor called EO at the tank and asked him to walk up the hill and put eyes on the leak. After a short time, he then called to EO at the truck to shut the bleach off at the truck as the leak turned out to be a bleach leak. Shift Supervisor then went to the lake area to check on the leak and several olhers began showing up to inspect. Calls to Environmental Coordinator and plant manager were made. The truckwas relocated to the unloading site adjacent to the product storage tank and the balance of the load was transfei,ed without incident. Calculations performed as to loss of material were done and reportable quantity called in by plant env coordinator to NRC, Texas Commission on Environmental Quality(TCEQ), and Titus Fire Dept.
column169: Bulk tank fill pipe was immediately put out of service. Risk analysis to be perfonned on the replacement of piping forthe remote fill station to continue usage with upgrades on piping and installation practices to be investigated. Engineering analysis to be performed on new fill station in doser proximity to chemical tank. Consideration of alternative bleach injection location will be ^^^^^^^n^ignee will take into consideration the different scenarios and make adecision as to the safest option for future

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: Rail car BCCX 100126 was loaded at our facility in Winnipeg, Manitoba on February 16th, 2021. The temperature in Winnipeg at that time was around-33 degrees F. After the rail car was loaded, it was pressure tested to 40 PSI for 10 minutes. The rail car was released to the CN Railway later that day. The rail car arrived in International Falls at 00:31 CST on February 23rd. The high temperature in International Falls on February 23rd was 39 degrees F. Border Chemical received a call from Mr. Jared Ginter, Safety Director, Boise White Paper, LLC, at approx. 12:15 CST on February 23rd notifying us that the rail car appeared to be dripping sulphuric acid. Mr. Ginter indicated that the leak was very slow, and he had placed a pail under the rail car to capture the dripping sulphuric acid. We had an experienced driver(Mr. Gerald Parisien-31 years with Border Chemical delivering and handling sulphuric acid) in the area at the time and diverted him to International Falls to investigate the situation. Mr. Parisien arrived on site at approx. 14:00 that day. After donning his PPE, Mr. Parisien climbed up on the rail car and immediately noticed sulphuric acid slowly Ieaking from under the eductor pipe cap and determined that this was a non-accident related release. At that time Mr. Parisian phoned our office and spoke with our plant superintendent, Mr. Greg Zahayko. Based on the area of the leak, Mr. Zahayko determined that due to the extreme temperature fluctuation, pressure had built up in the railcar and this had forced the sulphuric acid up the eductor pipe, causing the leak. Mr. Zahayko had Mr. Parisien tighten the eductor pipe cap approx. ^ tum, and that stopped the leak. Mr. Ginter supplied some Iime to Mr. Parisien, and he spread the Iime under the rail car to neutralize any residue that might have leaked onto the ground. Mr. Ginter disposed of the small amount of acid captured in the pail that was placed under the rail car. Mr. Ginter estimated that approx. 1.5 gallons of sulphuric acid had leaked from the rail car.
column169: In the future when loading sulphuric acid in rail cars during extreme cold weather events, we will ensure that all gaskets on the rail cars are replaced with new gaskets, and not reuse existing gaskets.

column169: 1.)  Went over the acid loading procedures with all 5 other RIVR drivers to make sure they understood them and that they are NEVER to touch the loading screen until the spout is in the dome.  2.)  Had an one hour meeting with the driver involved.  We went over the procedures to determine what went wrong.  Driver admits he was thinking steps ahead of himself.    3.)  Driver was given a 3-day suspension and warned that ANY further problems at Chemtrade will result in permanent ban from their property and immediate termination from GTI.  4.)  Phone meeting was held 2/2 with Bobby Lensing at GTI and Craig Tylenda (Chemtrade RIVR Plant Manager). We will discuss modifying Acid Truck Loading Checklist to clarify a couple of steps and avoid confusion.

column168: SequenceEvent: I responded to a paint leaker that was found on the unload. Immediately I responded by grabbing a tote lined with a plastic bag and my cart. I grabbed leaking box from the dock, then I put it in my tote and pushed my damaged package to my table. At the table is where I realized this package was a hazmat and proceeding to grab white towels, hazardous waste bag and put on my blue disposable gloves. After getting prepared, I cut package label off from box, ripped off its flammable sticker and hazardous materials shipping papers. I proceeded to contain the leaking paint by puting it in hazardous waste bag, tied bag and contents with zip ties and did this twice due to the bag being ripped. After containing the leaking hazmat I then put it in a yellow drum and kept in in the hazmat cage, so I could continue processing the damaged hazmat. DescribePack: Upon inspection of the damaged hazmat I saw it rapidly leaking from the bottom of its metal pail. The inner packaging was protruding, dented metal which caused it to leak and rip 3 of the plastic bags that I had contained it in. Estimated roughly half of the hazardous paint was lost due to damage. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: By containing the leak with 3 plastic bags, two of which were hazardous waste bags helped in containing the leak from spreading everywhere. Immediately I bagged and put paint into yellow drum which aided in leak being contained to plastic bags I used.

SequenceEvent: hazmat admin began work at 1:00pm and discovered package in a lined tote in the incoming damaged hazmat area. near it was another lined tote full of used absorbent powder. hazmat admin presumes that these go together. a quick glance at package shows that the bottom is soaked. ftrack shows that package received an inbound scan at 8:34am. it appears that package became damaged after this and before it could be scanned to a van. cleanup appears to have been performed as quickly as possible and the used powder kept next to the damaged package. inhouse cleanup, awaiting disposition. DescribePack: package contains four 4L glass bottles. a top and bottom tray made of molded pulp are the only packing material.  one glass bottle broke. unable to determine whether this was due to mishandling/drop or if the glass bottles were able to touch each other. DurationRel: 4 and MitigateEffect: whoever handled this at the time of initial damage placed the package into a lined tote so that any further liquid would be captured inside the liner.  when hazmat admin who came in at 1pm found it, that admin carefully moved the package onto a drain mat so as to pour the additional leaked liquid into the used powder, then moved package back into lined tote. now both totes are kept next to each other on large plastic tray atop a drain mat.

SequenceEvent: Our station has experienced consecutive days of sub zero temps. Packages arriving tp and being held here at the station have been exposed to these temperatures. We have deduced that this package and the contents were exposed to these low temperatures resulting in the contents freezing and the liquid contents inside burst the plastic jug/bottle packaging resulting in the release of the liquid into the fiberboard packaging and out onto the concrete flooring. Once the leaking package was discovered, a HazMat certified QA worker picked up the package and placed it into a plastic lined red bin labeled Hazardous Materials. The red bin was then moved to the HazMat area of the QA cage for later processing. DescribePack: The package contained 10 2 liter plastic bottles/jugs with a plastic screw on lid/cap. Each plastic bottle was inside a fiberboard box. There were 10 of these fiberboard boxes inside the outer packaging box. The failure occurred on 1 of the plastic bottles, specifically the plastic cap/lid cracked and broke into pieces. We assume the the liquid inside the bottle froze and burst the plastic cap. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: The entire HazMat package was placed into a red bin marker Hazardous Materials lined with plastic. The plastic bag was closed and the package was stored upright.

column168: SequenceEvent: Upon my arrival at 0530 on 02/17/21, the belt manager informed me there was a damaged hazmat paint can left over from Outbound sort that was not processed. It had leaked onto the floor but did not seem to be currently leaking. My inspection of the area I concluded that the can was put onto the IC rollers and tipped over while being pushed. Leaking paint came out of the seam of where the handle connects to the metal pail. Paint leaked on the rollers and onto the floor. Someone stepped in the puddle on the floor and left footprints across the floor for about 5 yards. The can actively leaks out of the handle seam when slightly tipped over. I cannot assess how much has leaked because I cannot open the metal can. Can was moved into the hazmat cage for processing. DescribePack: The seam of where the handle connects to the 5gallon metal pail leaks paint. Reasoning unknown. Small dent on bottom does not seem to be significant enough to affect where the paint is leaking out. cannot inspect further to asses what caused damage or how much leaked due to the type of metal can. it cannot be opened at the facility. Do not have the correct tools. DurationRel: 12 and MitigateEffect: I put absorbent pads on the foot prints and on the puddle. attempted to clean off the rollers that were affected, however the paint had long dried on them and could not be taken off.

column168: SequenceEvent: I responded to a paint leaker that was found on the unload. Immediately I responded by grabbing a tote lined with a plastic bag and my cart. I grabbed leaking box from the dock, then I put it in my tote and pushed my damaged package to my table. At the table is where I realized this package was a hazmat and proceeding to grab white towels, hazardous waste bag and put on my blue disposable gloves. After getting prepared, I cut package label off from box, ripped off its flammable sticker and hazardous materials shipping papers. I proceeded to contain the leaking paint by puting it in hazardous waste bag, tied bag and contents with zip ties and did this twice due to the bag being ripped. After containing the leaking hazmat I then put it in a yellow drum and kept in in the hazmat cage, so I could continue processing the damaged hazmat. DescribePack: Upon inspection of the damaged hazmat I saw it rapidly leaking from the bottom of its metal pail. The inner packaging was protruding, dented metal which caused it to leak and rip 3 of the plastic bags that I had contained it in. Estimated roughly half of the hazardous paint was lost due to damage. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: By containing the leak with 3 plastic bags, two of which were hazardous waste bags helped in containing the leak from spreading everywhere. Immediately I bagged and put paint into yellow drum which aided in leak being contained to plastic bags I used.

Crews utilized hand tools to scrape off additional product that had dried on the trailer floor. UST personnel transferred the three(3) intact 55-gallon drums in the shipment onto a new pallet and secured with plastic wrap. The impacted pallet was cut and containerized within one(1) 35-gallon drum for disposal. UST collected all additional impacted materials and containerized them within the previously generated 35-gallon drum for disposal. Both drums wen left on-site for RLC to manage disposal. UST repalletized and wrapped all undamaged cargo, then transferred ownership of the waste drum to RLC for future bulk waste disposal. With the site returned to prerelease conditions, UST demobilized, noting no further actions required.

column168: Package was received at our shipping dock from a customer with a cockpit voice/data recorder(CVFDR) inside the package. The 90 day beacon on the CVFDR contains 1.75g lithium metal content so this was a lithium metal battery packaged in equipment shipment. Package had no markings that it was a dangerous goods/hazardous materials shipment nor was the Shippers Declaration present. Our shipping department personnel unpackaged the unit and delivered the unit to our repair department. We notified the shipper they shipped a dangerous good without the proper labels and documentation and that they needed to remedy this in the future and that Universal Avionics was required to r6port the incident. There was no release. We are outside the 30 day reporting window due to a change in personnel completing the report.
column169: Our personnel have received training on recognizing hazardous materials arriving at our dock with issues and to ^ notify management when an incident occurs. We provided additional training to recognize when a hazardous material arrives without the appropriate markings or documentation and no release and to immediately report it to management so we can capture all the appropriate information in 6rder to report the incident. We have also notified customers and dealers through newsletters, a notice on our customer website and a service bulletin about reshipping this particular product for repairs and the need to ship as dangerous goods/hazardous material.

column168: On February 3, 2021, personnel at the R+L Carriers(RLC) terminal located at the above-referenced address observed a cargo leak in trailer OA3120 located at dock door 43. Upon further inspection, one(1) 5-gallon pail of UN3266 degreaser concentrate was damaged by an adjacent pallet in transit and released approximately five(5) gallons of product to the trailer interior. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC((DES), who dispatched a crew from EnviroServe(ES) to perform the necessary corrective action. ES identified one(1) damaged 5-gallon container and one(1) heavily impacted 5-gallon container. The two(2) containers were removed from the pallet for disposal and the pallet reconstructed. ES deployed absorbents to the release and swept them in with hand tools. All waste was collected and containerized into two(2) 55-gallon drums and left onsite for disposal by terminal personnel. Once the cleanup was complete, ES secured the scene and demobilized.

column168: On February 4, 2021, personnel at the R+L Carriers(RLC) terminal located at the above-referenced address observed a cargo leak in trailer LE1529 located at dock door 122. Upon further inspection, one(1) 275-gallon tote of Winterized Roadmaster diesel fuel additive was damaged and released approximately five(5) gallons of product to the trailer interior. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CES), who dispatched a crew from UST Environmental Contractor(UST) to perform the necessary corrective action. UST set up a containment area to perform a tote transfer and utilized a forklift to perform a gravity transfer of the product from the damaged 275-gallon poly tote into a new 275-gallon poly tote. The empty tote was shrink wrapped for disposal. Crews deployed granular absorbents to the release and swept them in with hand tools. All cleanup waste and debris were containerized into three(3) 35-gallon poly drums. The waste drums and empty tote were staged onsite for disposal by terminal personnel. Once the cleanup was complete, UST secured the scene and demobilized.

column168: The tractor/tanker trailer combination was traveling westbound on I255 in lane 3, hauling approximately 7300 gallons of diesel fuel, enroute to Cape Girardeau, MO. The driver believes he fell asleep, causing him to lose control of the vehicle. The vehicle crossed two lanes of traffic , ran off the left side of the interstate, struck the concrete median barrier, overturned and crossed into the eastbound lanes of I255. Emergency vehicles responded, extricated and transported the driver to the hospital, controlled traffic, shut down the interstate, and cleaned up any hazardous materials from the roadway. There was diesel fuel on the roadway, primarily from the saddle tanks of the tractor, but there was also a small amount of leakage from a dome on top of the cargo tank. On site environmental responders estimated approximately 15 gallons of diesel fuel had leaked onto the roadway. By 0950, the crashed vehicle had been cleared, scene cleaned up, interstate opened back up, and all emergency vehicles had left the scene.  Emergency response efforts included stopping and securing the dome drip leak by using cribbing for stabilization and diking the fuel spill to contain the spill area to mitigate damages. Another tractor/tanker trailer combination was brought on scene to transfer the hauled product from the crashed tanker to its final destination.
column169: We recommend to remind drivers to ensure they have the proper rest. If they indicate they have issues getting the proper rest, encourage them to make adjustments to their sleep patterns and/or bedroom to make rest a priority and voluntarily complete a sleep study.
